&lt;p>&#xD;
    Risks can be actioned in one of the following ways:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Remove - Risk can be removed from the project by changing the solution's characteristics.&amp;nbsp; For example, risk&#xD;
        due to the use of an unproved development tool can be removed by substituting a proven tool.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Accept - Risks can be accepted without a change to the architecture.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Contain - Adding estimation contingency, mitigation tasks, excess capacity or other measures to reduce the&#xD;
        probability of a risk occurring can contain risks.&amp;nbsp; For example, risk due to geographically distributed&#xD;
        development sites can be mitigated by developing a workroom, conducting standing joint meetings, etc. The risk,&#xD;
        though, remains an inherent characteristic of the proposed solution.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;strong>4.&amp;nbsp;Architecture Checklist&lt;/strong>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Checklist or questionnaire should be created to structure and organize the viability assessment.&amp;nbsp; This is used to&#xD;
    uncover the major items that will be documented in the General Recommendations and Findings section.&amp;nbsp; A suggested&#xD;
    checklist is provided in the Validation and Verification section of this work product.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;strong>5.&amp;nbsp;Recommendation for Next Review&lt;/strong>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Document the anticipated date for the next review so that participants and project management can plan&#xD;
    accordingly.&amp;nbsp; The need for a follow-up review will depend upon the specification in the project's engagement&#xD;
    template, the seriousness of the findings, and/or any external IBM QA policies. More Information.&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
